[Since the last ProMED-mail update on polio earlier this week (Poliomyelitis - update (23): Syria susp., global, RFI 20131020.2010654), the number of suspected cases of polio in Syria has increased from 10 to 22, suggesting that there has been significant circulation of poliovirus in the affected area. Confirmation of wild poliovirus (WPV) by the regional polio reference laboratory is still pending.

Another significant occurrence during this past week is the confirmation of WPV infection in Cameroon. Genetic studies on this isolate are still pending but most likely will be similar to those WPVs circulating in Nigeria, one of the 3 remaining polio endemic countries in the world.

As discussed in the above Global Polio Eradication Initiative update, the common denominator that seems to be impeding eradication efforts worldwide is the presence of civil unrest in a number of countries that had led to serious gaps in immunization coverages of the susceptible population.

For a map showing the location of confirmed WPV cases in 2013, see http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Poliocasesworldwide.aspx.

The province (governorate) of Deir al-Zor (Dayr az Zawr) can be seen on the map at http://www.ephotopix.com/syria_province_map.html. It is located in the northeast of the country, bordering with Iraq. If WPV is confirmed, given the civil unrest in Iraq, one wonders if there might be WPV circulating across the border in Iraq as well.

For the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Syria, see http://healthmap.org/r/8S1u. - Mod.MPP]
